        "body": "The opening *hinneh* ('Behold') is a particle of immediate address — it arrests attention and frames what follows as urgent and present. The most natural reading of the psalm's liturgical setting (attested in older commentators from Delitzsch onward, and elaborated by Allen Ross and Leslie Allen) is that the departing pilgrims speak verses 1-2 as their farewell to the Levitical night-watch servants who remain at the Temple. The pilgrims have worshiped, the festival has concluded, and they now address those who will continue the ministry through the night. The imperative 'bless the LORD' is plural — addressed to a community of servants, the *col avadei yehovah* ('all servants of the LORD'), echoing the same phrase in Psalm 113:1 and 135:1.\n\nThe servants addressed are identified specifically as those 'who serve (*amad*) by night.' The verb *amad* — to stand, to take one's station — is the technical term for Levitical ministry (Deuteronomy 10:8; 2 Chronicles 29:11). To stand before the LORD was not casual proximity; it was official, consecrated appointment. 1 Chronicles 9:33 confirms that singers and their relatives 'were employed in their work day and night.' Nehemiah 11:19 similarly speaks of gatekeepers keeping 'watch at the gates.' The night watch was not a lesser form of ministry — it was the hidden backbone of the Temple's continuous worship.\n\nThe theological claim embedded in this verse is that worship is not contingent on a favorable audience. The night-watch servants minister when no crowd of pilgrims is present, when no festival energy sustains them, when the only witness is God Himself. The psalm dignifies this hidden faithfulness by making it the subject of its final summons. Spurgeon, in The Treasury of David, writes on Psalm 134: 'Some must keep watch. Let those who watch for the morning also watch for the LORD.' The summons to bless God by night is the psalm's pastoral spine.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Hinneh* — deictic particle of immediacy ('Behold, Come, Look'). *Barakh* (bless) — root meaning to kneel; as directed toward God it means to ascribe worth, to praise, to honor. *Eved* (servants) — the full weight of the covenant-servant relationship is in view. *Amad* (serve/stand) — used for Levitical station-taking in Deut 10:8 and 2 Chr 29:11."
